courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course, students will be able to:
(1) understand the basic concepts and theories of communication in a global setting;
(2) understand the definition, history, and current status of globalization;
(3) examine how media communications relate to the social, cultural, economic, and political aspects of globalization;
(4) acquire a basic understanding of the global information and media flows.

By the end of the course, students should:

1. Have basic and critical understanding of different mass communication theories;
2. Know the various roles of the mass media in society;
3. Be able to organize and present their own ideas and arguments in tutorial, essay writing and group project;
4. Have their own points of view on social phenomena related to the mass media;
5. Able to theorize about mass communication phenomena in our daily lives;
6. Know how to think like a social scientist.

By the end of the course, students will:

1. Acquire a theoretical grounding in strategic communication and socio-political campaigns;
2. Acquire the essential knowledge and practical skills to apply public communication and persuasive messaging in a campaign setting;
3. Acquire hands-on experience in applying advertising and public relations skills for campaigning;
4. Acquire on-the-ground experience in mounting a campaign;.

5. Be equipped with campaign leadership and problem solving skills.

6. Be equipped with interpersonal, teamwork, and social skills.

7. Be equipped with multimedia production and presentation skills.

8. Develop socio-political and cultural competences to critically examine the complex social and commercial issues in modern societies.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

(1) understand the basic concepts and theories of communication in a global setting;
(2) understand the definition, history, and current status of globalization;
(3) examine how media communications relate to the social, cultural, economic, and political aspects of globalization;
(4) acquire a basic understanding of the global information and media flows.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

(1) understand the key social, economic, and political issues that are “global” in character;
(2) understand the connections between seemingly local public affairs and their global contexts;
(3) analyze public issues in global perspectives

courses.course_syllabus:
(For reference only, subject to change)

The following topics will be covered by the course:

(1) international trade, business, and finance, as well as their regulations

(2) technology and media;
(3) migration, tourism, and refugee issues;
(4) energy, environment, and health;
(5) international law, human rights, gender issues; and

(6) international cooperation, conflicts and collective behaviors

(7) The role of multinational corporations and cross-national institutions in global affairs

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. Understand how worldviews, values, and beliefs are shaped by the way the media reports on them;
2. Discern the merits of various forms of news coverage in dealing with public debates;
3. Perceive the full extent of the many challenges, both technical and non-technical, facing the media in covering controversies;
4. Appreciate the full extent of the role the media plays in shaping public debate.

After taking this course, students should be able to:
(1) gain basic film knowledge, including film language, camera skills, film appreciation and the method and framework of film criticism;
(2) understand and reflect on Hong Kong history, Hong Kong society through the lens of film, as well as having a better understanding in arts and culture;
(3) appreciate films from different angles, such as class, gender, cultural identity and identity politics; and
(4) have a full understanding of Hong Kong cinema with knowledge in the capital, technology, industry of film, as well as production and consumption.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. Have a sound knowledge on storytelling with sound and video;
2. Acquire skills in interview techniques, presentations of stories in broadcast media;
3. Produce up-to-standard radio and television news;
4. Acquire concepts of media convergence and different digital platforms; and
5. Have a sense on what professional broadcast journalism is.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. Have a sound knowledge on storytelling with sound and video;
2. Acquire skills in interview techniques, presentations of stories in broadcast media;
3. Produce up-to-standard radio and television news;
4. Acquire concepts of media convergence and different digital platforms; and
5. Have a sense on what professional broadcast journalism is.

Upon successful completion of this course, students are expected to acquire the following outcomes:

* *Remembering:**

• The characteristics of an organizational crisis;

• The types of crisis in modern societies;

* *Understanding**

• A full understanding of the consequence a crisis can have on the reputation and

success of businesses and organizations;

* *Analyzing and applying**

• Ability to identify key messages, formulate appropriate responses and utilize

practical techniques to communicate with stakeholders about crisis situations;

• Skills necessary to address the issues when a crisis situation demands immediate

public response;

• Understanding of the dynamics and implications of various public relations

strategies;

• Mastery of relevant theories, as well as practical techniques and planning

necessary to successfully communicate before, during and after a crisis situation.

• Understanding how the Internet has facilitated the rising collective power of

consumers and commercial democracy in modern societies.

* *Synthesizing and creating**

· Creating effective crisis communication plans to handle crises;

· Utilizing the social media platform to restore corporate image and reputation in the post-crisis stage.

After taking this course, students will be able to:

(1) describe and explain the roles of Internet in the formation of the contemporary society and how it leads to social change;

(2) discuss various social and cultural phenomena in relation to the development of Internet;

(3) evaluate different claims about the impact of communication technologies in information society;

(4) identify and analyze core debates about Internet, digital media and information society; and

(5) become an informed and ethical user in the new media environment.

By the end of the course, students should:

(1) understand the basic operation of a media organization;
(2) learn the relevant knowledge and techniques;
(3) gain hands-on experiences as a media practitioner; and

(4) know more about the roles and functions of the media as well as professional ethics.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. Develop a basic understanding of key financial concepts and how the global capital markets function, interact, and communicate;
2. Analyze and interpret basic financial statements and understand the interaction between strategy and financial outcome;
3. Select and apply key tools of fundamental analysis and valuation metric; and
4. Apply financial knowledge in professional communication contexts, including journalism and public relations.

After completing this course, students should be able to:

1. have a basic understanding of different kinds of investigative reporting;
2. develop story ideas from the news and daily life;
3. learn and use various tools for investigative reporting;
4. know what it means to conduct investigative reporting that is solid and based on good facts, and its importance; and
5. gain experiences in investigative reporting.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. Examine culture and communication from different practical and theoretical perspectives;
2. Examine how worldviews, values, and beliefs become manifest in everyday communication;
3. Understand how media representations contribute to marginalization of particular groups;
4. Practice intercultural communication skills; and
5. Critique theoretical approaches to studying culture and communication as well as particular sociopolitical practices in contemporary societies around the world.

After completing this course, students should be able to:

1. gain good knowledge of the essential concepts of media ethics and law, and its application through case studies;
2. reflect upon work related issues from a media practitioner's perspective after comparative study of case laws in class on the topics that would cover important media ethical problems and legal issues;
3. acquire a better understanding of the vital values in media ethics and importance of major media laws that have significant bearing on digital media professionals; and
4. understand the ethical and legal issues of digital platforms and online data, and be able to identify critical elements of these topics.

After taking the course, students should:

1. Be familiar with studio camera operations to create effective images and be able to recognize some key shooting terminologies;

2. Be capable of writing TV scripts, storyboarding, rundown design and programming;

3. Be capable of directing a TV studio show;

4. Be able to perform basic skills in operating different studio equipment, such as lighting, audio control, floor management, etc;

5. Be able to master and complete a TV studio production.

By the end of the course, the students are expected to display the following outcomes:

(1) A good understanding of the operation of media industry;
(2) An ability to dissect the local media landscape;
(3) An adoption of a public relations perspective to dissect media messages;
(4) A good understanding of the relationships between public relations and the media;
(5) Effective practical skills in crafting messages for various media channels

By the end of this course, students should have developed a deeper understanding and enhanced appreciation of how the law fits in with the public relations practice. In particular, students will:

i) Learn the basic principles in areas of law closely related to public relations by understanding the (1) the elements that amount to the legal issue, (2) the possible defences and (3) consequences if liability if found;

ii) Understand the risks of disclosing too much or too little information to the public during a crisis – and the detriment it may have to either public relations or the legal aspect of the situation;

iii) Be able to notice red-flags in public relations messages and point out the specifics that may attract legal liability for practitioners and/or the organization;

iv) Learn when to seek legal advice in midst of a crisis and how serious the legal advice should be considered from a public relations perspective;

v) Learn how to craft a public relations message as to balance public opinion without causing legal liability to the organization;

vi) Understand the advantages and disadvantages to alternative dispute resolutions that may be able to help public relation practitioners avoid public legal disputes.

After taking the course, students will be able to:

1) Understand the role of advertising and the role of different media channels in driving brands' business in this fast-changing world;

2) Put together an outcome/ objective driven advertising media plan;

3) Articulate the key enablers in terms of creative, analytics and data and technology in driving the outcome of advertising; and

4) Manage advertising media solution from professional advertising and growth agency perspective

After completing this course, students should be able to:
1) record sound on location with basic equipment;
2) use appropriate software for recording, editing and mixing;
3) produce soundtracks for film, TV, radio and other creative media; and
4) use sound creatively in storytelling.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. Understand key theoretical approaches to studying digital platforms;
2. Gain a situated understanding of the historical trajectories and current practices of various global digital platforms;
3. Examine how digital platforms have reconfigured economic, cultural, and political environments;
4. Recognize and evaluate the social and ethical challenges of using, researching, and regulating digital platforms; and
5. Develop a critical voice on pressing controversies surrounding digital platforms from a global perspective.

By the end of the course, students should gain a clear understanding of the concepts and techniques of statistical analysis. Students should be able to:
• Use SPSS to perform statistical analysis;
• Choose appropriate statistical techniques to perform hypothesis tests;
• Perform and interpret various statistical tests including Z test, t-tests, analysis of variance, nonparametric tests, correlation and regression analyses; and
• Report the results of a statistical analysis.

By the end of the course, students should gain a clear understanding of qualitative methodology in communication, which includes:
• Focus group interview;
• Textual analysis;
• Ethnography; and
• Biographic methods.

By the end of the course, students are expected to:
• Gain a clear understanding of particular methods and their epistemological/ontological groundings;
• Apply the methods and make in-depth analyses;
• Read research that is using the approaches and evaluate the quality of it; and
• Apply one of the methods to their own conference paper/thesis/research proposals.
